# Three.js r160+ SRGB Compliance

Always check for r160+ Three.js compliance, specifically ensuring
SRGBColorSpace is used for all color outputs. This prevents the
"washed out" look common in production builds.

Concrete checklist when authoring or reviewing rendering code:
- Renderer: `gl.outputColorSpace = THREE.SRGBColorSpace` and
  `THREE.ColorManagement.enabled = true` (set once in the Canvas `onCreated`).
- Color textures (albedo / map / matcap): `tex.colorSpace = THREE.SRGBColorSpace`.
  Data textures (normal, roughness, AO, metalness, height) stay `THREE.NoColorSpace`.
- Any `new THREE.Color('#hex')` destined for a `ShaderMaterial` uniform OR a
  light/fog/background must be tagged: `color.colorSpace = THREE.SRGBColorSpace`.
  Use the shared helpers in `src/utils/srgbColor.ts` (`srgbColor(hex)` /
  `tagSrgb(color)`) — do not duplicate the tagging dance.
- Never call the legacy `tex.encoding = sRGBEncoding` or `renderer.outputEncoding`
  APIs — they were removed in r160.
